To avoid repeating the registration process and store the secretKeyReg for multiple login scenarios, you can modify your code to separate the registration step and the OTP generation step. You can create separate class **TwoFactorAuthentication** and pass the wedriver instance.

**Test Class example:**



    public class Test_Login {
        @Test
        public void loginUsing2FASuccessfulEmpPortal() {
            WebDriver driver = new ChromeDriver();
            TwoFactorAuthentication tfa = new TwoFactorAuthentication(driver);
    
            // Load employee portal URL
            driver.get(empPortalURL);
    
            // Login to employee portal
            driver.findElement(By.xpath(&quot;username&quot;)).click();
            driver.findElement(By.xpath(&quot;username&quot;)).sendKeys(&quot;test&quot;);
            driver.findElement(By.xpath(&quot;password&quot;)).sendKeys(&quot;test&quot;);
            driver.findElement(By.xpath(&quot;signin&quot;)).click();
    
            // Register for 2FA (if not already registered) and get the secret key
            String secretKey = tfa.registerFor2FA();
    
            // Enter OTP and sign in
            tfa.enterGeneratedOTP();
            driver.findElement(By.xpath(&quot;login&quot;)).click();
    
            // Assertion to check whether the user logged in successfully
        }
    }

you can create an instance of TwoFactorAuthentication by passing the WebDriver instance through the constructor, as shown below:


**TwoFactorAuthentication class:**


    package com.tests;
    
    import org.openqa.selenium.By;
    import org.openqa.selenium.WebElement;
    import org.openqa.selenium.WebDriver;
    
    import java.io.UnsupportedEncodingException;
    
    public class TwoFactorAuthentication {
        private String secretKeyReg;
        private WebDriver driver;
    
        public TwoFactorAuthentication(WebDriver driver) {
            this.driver = driver;
        }
    
        public String registerFor2FA() {
            // Register user to use 2FA
            // Login to website
            // Read secret key
            WebElement secretKey = driver.findElement(By.xpath(&quot;xpath&quot;));
            secretKeyReg = secretKey.getText();
    
            // Enter 2FA code to register
            String code = generateOTP();
            driver.findElement(By.xpath(&quot;2-step-setup-code&quot;)).click();
            driver.findElement(By.xpath(&quot;2-step-setup-code&quot;)).sendKeys(code);
            driver.findElement(By.xpath(&quot;done-button&quot;)).click();
    
            return secretKeyReg;
        }
    
        public void enterGeneratedOTP() {
            String code = generateOTP();
            driver.findElement(By.xpath(&quot;authentication-code&quot;)).click();
            driver.findElement(By.xpath(&quot;authentication-code&quot;)).sendKeys(code);
        }
    
    
        public String generateOTP() {
            try {
                // Generate OTP using the stored secret key (secretKeyReg)
                secretKeyReg = registerFor2FA();
                String secretKey = secretKeyReg;
                byte[] secret = secretKey.getBytes(&quot;UTF-8&quot;);
                TOTP.Builder builder = new TOTP.Builder(secret);
                builder.withPasswordLength(6)
                        .withAlgorithm(HMACAlgorithm.SHA1) // SHA256 and SHA512 are also supported
                        .withPeriod(Duration.ofSeconds(30));
    
                TOTP totp = builder.build();
                String code = totp.now(); // generate code
                return code;
            } catch (UnsupportedEncodingException e) {
                System.err.println(&quot;The character encoding is not supported.&quot;);
            }
            return &quot;&quot;;
        }
    }
Now, the TwoFactorAuthentication class will utilize the provided WebDriver instance throughout its methods.

